        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was ten. His father, smelling of garlic and cardamom, handed him a small pitcher of chilled *laban ayran*. \"For Mr. Azar,\" his father said, his eyes conveying the importance of the task. Sami carefully carried it to their oldest guest, pouring the yogurt drink without spilling a drop. The man\u2019s grateful smile felt like a warm light inside his own chest. It was his first taste of service, the quiet, profound joy of offering comfort. This feeling became his compass.\n\n2.\nIn a dusty Beaujolais cellar, the leathery-skinned vintner held a glass of Gamay to the light from a single bulb. He didn\u2019t discuss tasting notes; he spoke of the 200-year-old vines and a hailstorm his grandfather weathered. When Sami finally tasted it, he tasted the sun, the struggle, the history. It was the moment wine ceased to be a beverage and became a language. That single glass ignited an obsession that would define his entire career, a pursuit of story in a bottle.\n\n3.\nHis first week in San Francisco, walking to his job interview. He left his North Beach apartment, the air smelling of espresso and focaccia, passing Italian bakeries his family would adore. As he walked, the Transamerica Pyramid grew, slicing the sky. The contrast was exhilarating\u2014the cozy, historic neighborhood giving way to the steel and glass ambition of the Financial District. He knew, with absolute certainty, he was walking toward his future, a path connecting two worlds he now called home.\n\n4.\nTwo years into his career, the restaurant's general manager called him into the office after a long shift. \"The floor is yours now, Sami,\" she said, placing the small, silver *tastevin* in his hand. He felt the cool weight of it, a symbol he'd only dreamed of wearing. Walking home that night, he felt taller, the city lights reflecting in his eyes. It wasn't just a promotion; it was validation. It was proof that his palate, his passion, and his tireless study had been seen and honored.\n\n5.\nA nervous young couple, celebrating an anniversary, looked lost staring at the wine list. Sami\u2019s mind briefly flashed to his parents making guests feel at ease. He leaned in, not asking what they liked, but asking about their first date. He then chose a bottle, explaining how its bright, hopeful notes reminded him of new beginnings. Seeing their faces relax into shared joy, he wasn\u2019t just a sommelier. He was a Haddad, using wine to practice the sacred, simple art of hospitality."
